[[File:Moyoro Shell Midden.jpg|thumb|240px|right|Moyoro Shell Midden (April 2010)]] {{Coord|44|1|30.0|N|144|16|3.7|E|region:JP-01|display=title}} {{Location map|Japan Hokkaido|relief=1| lat_deg = 44| lat_min = 1| lat_sec = 30.0| lon_deg = 144| lon_min = 16| lon_sec = 3.7| label = Moyoro Shell Midden| position = top| mark = Red pog.svg| marksize = 10| width = 240| caption={{Center|}}}} '''Moyoro Shell Midden''' (モヨロ貝塚, Moyoro Kaizuka) is a representative {{ill|Okhotsk culture|ja|オホーツク文化|12=draft|12=draft}} archaeological site located in {{ill|Abashiri, Hokkaido|ja|網走市|12=draft|12=draft}}, extending from Kita 1-chome to Kita 3-chome Higashi 2-chome. Situated on the left bank of the {{ill|Abashiri River|ja|網走川|12=draft|12=draft}} near the Sea of Okhotsk, it is designated as a [[Historic Sites of Japan|national historic site]] (registered as '''Saiyo Shell Midden''').<ref group="note">In Hokkaido, other shell middens designated as national historic sites include: * {{ill|Higashi Kushiro Shell Midden|ja|東釧路貝塚|12=draft|12=draft}} (Kushiro City, designated in 1970) * {{ill|Kita Kogan Shell Midden|ja|北黄金貝塚|12=draft|12=draft}} (Date City, designated in 1987) * {{ill|Irie Shell Midden|ja|入江貝塚|12=draft|12=draft}} (Toyako Town, designated in 1988) * {{ill|Otayachi Shell Midden|ja|大谷地貝塚|12=draft|12=draft}} (Yoichi Town, designated in 2000)</ref> The name "Moyoro" was given by amateur archaeologist {{ill|Yonezawa Kioe|ja|米村喜男衛|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1918, inspired by the term "Moyoro Kotan," meaning "inlet place" in {{ill|Ainu language|ja|アイヌ語|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="takeda">Takeda Teruo, "Saiyo Shell Midden," in Bunkachō Bunka Zaihō-bu Shiseki Kenkyū-kai, ed., ''Illustrated History of Japan, Volume 1: Prehistory 1,'' Dōbōsha Publishing, 1991, p. 30.</ref>
== Overview == The site is located on a sandy plateau about five meters above sea level on the northern bank of the Abashiri River's mouth. Buildings were constructed during a period corresponding to the late {{ill|Jomon period|ja|縄文時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, continuing through the {{ill|Epi-Jomon culture|ja|続縄文時代|12=draft|12=draft}} and into the Okhotsk culture. {{ill|Pit dwellings|ja|竪穴建物|12=draft|12=draft}} were used as residences, while the deceased were buried in the {{ill|shell midden|ja|貝塚|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Large buildings associated with the Okhotsk culture contained arranged remains of {{ill|marine mammals|ja|海獣|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|brown bears|ja|ヒグマ|12=draft|12=draft}}, suggesting ceremonial or ritualistic practices. The shell midden has yielded numerous artifacts, including {{ill|bone tools|ja|骨角器|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|pottery|ja|土器|12=draft|12=draft}}, and stone implements. Artifacts of non-local origin include iron swords (e.g., {{ill|Chokutō|ja|直刀|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|warabite-to|ja|蕨手刀|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|mounuki-type swords|ja|毛抜形太刀|1=Kenukigata-tachi|12=draft|12=draft}}) and bronze bells believed to have been imported from the mainland. Artworks such as whale and bear carvings on tools and finely crafted ivory figurines, including a detailed walrus ivory female figure, have also been discovered.<ref group="note">The walrus ivory figurine is thought to have been introduced from the Primorsky Krai region.</ref><ref name="takeda"/> The predominance of tools suggests that marine mammal hunting was a central activity.
== Excavation History == The site was discovered in 1913 by amateur archaeologist Yonezawa Kioe, who reported its significance to academia. Yonezawa identified a cultural context distinct from {{ill|Jomon culture|ja|縄文文化|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Ainu culture|ja|アイヌ文化|12=draft|12=draft}} based on the discovered pottery.<ref group="note">Hiromichi Kawano classified pottery from Sakhalin, the Okhotsk coast, and the Kuril Islands, along with those from the Moyoro Shell Midden, into the ''Okhotsk-style pottery group'' with four types.</ref><ref name="dokigun">Wada Hideaki, "Moyoro Shell Midden," in Kobayashi Tatsuo, ed., ''Archaeological Handbook,'' Shinshokan, January 2007, p. 247.</ref>
In 1933, the unique "Okhotsk coastal culture" was recognized as distinct from contemporary Hokkaido cultures, later identified as the Okhotsk culture. A museum, the North Kitami Historical Museum (now {{ill|Abashiri Municipal Museum|ja|網走市立郷土博物館|12=draft|12=draft}}), was established in 1936 to preserve artifacts. The site was designated a national historic site on December 16, 1936.<ref>{{National Cultural Properties Database|401|22|Saiyo Shell Midden}}</ref><ref>[https://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/2959470/2 Ministry of Education Announcement No. 367, Showa Year 11, in ''Kanpō'' Issue 2988, p. 518]</ref>
During WWII, parts of the site were destroyed for naval construction, prompting emergency excavations. Over 100 human remains and numerous artifacts were recovered. Further excavations in the late 20th and early 21st centuries uncovered additional graves and cultivated plant seeds, including barley.<ref name="dokigun"/>
== Current Status == [[File:Moyoro Shell Midden Museum.jpg|thumb|240px|right|Moyoro Shell Midden Museum]] [[File:2013 Moyoro Shell Midden Museum.jpg|thumb|240px|Museum after its 2013 renovation]] The site has been developed into a park centered around the Moyoro Shell Midden Museum. Artifacts are also displayed at the Abashiri Municipal Museum. Recent excavations in 2003–2004 uncovered items such as earthen bear figurines. A new Moyoro Shell Midden Museum opened on May 1, 2013.<ref name="mainichi-np-2014-5-2">Yamada Yasuo (May 2, 2014). "New Moyoro Shell Midden Museum Opens: Exhibition Space Expands Sevenfold in Abashiri." ''Mainichi Shimbun'' (The Mainichi Newspapers).</ref>
== References == {{Reflist}} === Notes === {{Reflist|group="note"}}
== Further Reading == * Yonezawa Kioe, ''Moyoro Kaizuka Materials Collection,'' Abashiri Municipal Museum and Nomura Shoten, 1950. * Komai Kazue, ed., ''Okhotsk Coastal Sites and Shiretoko Peninsula, Vol. 2,'' Tokyo University Faculty of Letters, 1964. * Yonezawa Ei, ''People of the Northern Seas: Moyoro Shell Midden,'' Shinzen Publishing, 2004. ISBN 4787704311.
== Related Articles == * {{ill|Shell midden|ja|貝塚|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Orochon Fire Festival|ja|オロチョンの火祭り|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|List of shell middens in Japan|ja|日本の貝塚一覧|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Kaido o Yuku|ja|街道をゆく|12=draft|12=draft}} (Detailed discussion on Yonezawa's work in "Okhotsk Kaido.")
== External Links == * [http://sapporo.cool.ne.jp/hakubutukanntomono/ Abashiri Municipal Museum Friends Association (Archived)] * [http://inoues.net/ruins/moyoro_kaiduka.htm Moyoro Shell Midden]
